382":"1340–1382","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","before 1340":"before 1340","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1320":"about 1320","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Doull","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Caithness): from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i> (see   Donald  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Doull was born about 1320, in Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Elizabeth Wood before 1340, in Lanarkshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1320–":"umbes 1320–Surnud","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","before 1340":"enne 1340","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1320":"umbes 1320","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1320–":"noin 1320–Kuollut","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","before 1340":"ennen vuotta 1340","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1320":"noin 1320","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1320–":"environ 1320–Décédé","1323–Female":"1323–Décédée","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","before 1340":"avant 1340","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1320":"environ 1320","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Écosse","Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Richard Doull est né environ 1320, à Stonehouse, Lanarkshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Elizabeth Wood avant 1340, à Lanarkshire, Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1320–":"um 1320–Verstorben","1323–Female":"1323–Verstorben","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1320–Male":"1320–Verstorben","1323":"1323"